atoms.title: Analysis Of Top K
atoms.instructor_notes:
There's lots of ways to get the 4n before you prove that it is correct.  One is to start by doing what several people did in the earlier unit---make some plots to get a good guess of the function.  That gets you the "n".  Then, you can try pushing it through with c n and you find that 1 + 3/4 c <= c for things to work out.  Solving that, you get c >= 4.  -MLL

As discussed in the forum, this analysis is problematic---it is not equally likely for the k-th largest element to be in the larger or smaller piece after the split.  If k is close to 1 or n, it is much more likely to fall into the larger piece.  On the forum, I posted an analysis that doesn't suffer from this problem at the expense of a higher constant: 9. -MLL

atoms.title: Heaps Of Fun
atoms.instructor_notes:
No, I got this wrong.  A heap is a particular data structure.  It is used to implement a "priority queue", which is an abstract data type.  Sorry about that.  -MLL

In my experiments with python, deleting the first element of L using "del L[0]" appears to be constant time, Theta(1).  Using "L = L[1:]" appears to involving a copy and is Theta(n). -MLL
